  "local_port": 39200,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I get Scrum Master certification?",
  "response": "Obtaining a Scrum Master certification typically involves several steps. Here\u2019s a general guide to help you achieve this:\n\n1. **Understand the Role**: It's essential to have a clear understanding of what a Scrum Master does. The role involves facilitating Scrum practices, helping teams work effectively, removing obstacles, and ensuring that the Scrum framework is followed.\n\n2. **Choose the Right Certification**: There are several organizations that offer Scrum Master certifications. The most recognized ones are:\n   - **Certified ScrumMaster (CSM)** from Scrum Alliance\n   - **Professional Scrum Master (PSM)** from Scrum.org\n   - **SAFe Scrum Master (SSM)** from Scaled Agile\n   - **Scrum Master Certified (SMC)** from ScrumStudy\n\n3. **Take a Course**: Most certifications require you to take a course. These courses can be in-person or online and usually last two days. They cover the Scrum framework and the duties of a Scrum Master. Some options include:\n   - **CSM**: Requires attendance in a two-day course led by a Certified Scrum Trainer (CST).\n   - **PSM**: Offers courses but is not mandatory before taking the exam. Scrum.org provides multiple levels of PSM certification.\n\n4. **Study**: Review the Scrum Guide thoroughly, regardless of the certification you choose. It's important to have a firm understanding of Scrum principles, roles, events, and artifacts.\n\n5. **Take the Exam**: After completing the prerequisite course, you'll need to pass an exam. Here's how it generally goes:\n   - **CSM**: You\u2019ll receive a link to the online CSM test after completing the course. You have to answer 50 multiple-choice questions within 60 minutes and need to score at least 74% to pass.\n   - **PSM**: You can take the exam directly on the Scrum.org website. The PSM I exam consists of 80 questions that you need to complete in 60 minutes. A passing score is 85%.\n\n6. **Maintain Certification**: Some certifications require renewal to maintain their status:\n   - **CSM**: Needs renewal every two years with a fee and involves earning Scrum Education Units (SEUs).\n   - **PSM**: Does not require renewal once you achieve it.\n\n7. **Gain Experience**: While earning the certification is a crucial step, practical experience is invaluable. Work with a Scrum team, get involved in real projects, and continue learning and adapting to different environments.\n\nBy following these steps, you\u2019ll be well on your way to becoming a certified Scrum Master. Remember to choose the certification that best aligns with your career goals and interests.",
